      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>WESTCHESTER readers didn't hesitate to take the pyrameter challenge presented by this section's editors May 7.</p>
        <p>They submitted close to 100 samples of the poetry form invented by John Chervokas, the Ossining town supervisor.</p>
        <p>His rules: 9 lines, 45 syllables, with one syllable in the first line and each subsequent line increasing by an additional syllable so that last line says nine. Mr. Chervokas pointed out in a letter that was published May 14: the fifth line should be the title.</p>
        <p>Our rules, which readers more or less followed: write about something connected to Westchester. Here is a sampling of the poems submitted.</p>
        <p>My</p>
        <p>wife plants</p>
        <p>a rose bush</p>
        <p>while I bring home</p>
        <p>a new red Mustang.</p>
        <p>Blood and petals, beside</p>
        <p>each other in the driveway.</p>
        <p>Two brazen visions of power,</p>
        <p>each with internal combustion.</p>
        <p>BOB GAFFNEY, Pelham Manor</p>
        <p>Would</p>
        <p>it be</p>
        <p>a problem</p>
        <p>if I brought my</p>
        <p>dog along with me?</p>
        <p>He hates to be alone</p>
        <p>you see, so could he be an</p>
        <p>invitee? And put an end to</p>
        <p>cries of oh! you have forgotten me.</p>
        <p>DEBORAH YAGODA, Mohegan Lake</p>
        <p>A</p>
        <p>driver</p>
        <p>on the road</p>
        <p>going fast to</p>
        <p>get the kids to school.</p>
        <p>The most dangerous car</p>
        <p>on the highway today is</p>
        <p>the suburban mother who is</p>
        <p>10 minutes behind schedule.</p>
        <p>KATE PERMUT, Scarborough</p>
        <p>Far</p>
        <p>below</p>
        <p>the hissing</p>
        <p>pistons -- beneath</p>
        <p>the tin can static;</p>
        <p>somewhere, under the drum</p>
        <p>of my rush-hour migraine.</p>
        <p>I think of you and all I hear</p>
        <p>is the sweet music of reunion.</p>
        <p>BRUCE MYINT, Riverdale</p>
        <p>Sand</p>
        <p>piles up</p>
        <p>the wet beach</p>
        <p>forming castles</p>
        <p>palaces for kings</p>
        <p>drawbridges and towers</p>
        <p>capturing the brilliant sun,</p>
        <p>the wet legs and smiling faces</p>
        <p>in its moats of blue frothy water</p>
        <p>SARA HUGHES, Grade 12  Pelham Memorial High School</p>
        <p>Tell</p>
        <p>the world</p>
        <p>poetry</p>
        <p>is alive and</p>
        <p>will light up your nights</p>
        <p>like a memory of</p>
        <p>childhoods gone, when evening</p>
        <p>meant asking your mom to go out</p>
        <p>and find fireflies before bedtime.</p>
        <p>MARSHA JAMIL, White Plains</p>
        <p>Please</p>
        <p>be sure</p>
        <p>that the valves</p>
        <p>that secure the</p>
        <p>nuclear fuel rods</p>
        <p>are in working order</p>
        <p>24 hours each day so</p>
        <p>we may live here safely and watch</p>
        <p>our children find their adulthood.</p>
        <p>DR. LEILA NOVAK, Hastings-on-Hudson</p>
        <p>Hi!</p>
        <p>Nice place</p>
        <p>Westchester</p>
        <p>Well-structured lawns</p>
        <p>constantly nibbled</p>
        <p>houses hidden by trees</p>
        <p>newest cars in the driveways,</p>
        <p>their owners made anxious</p>
        <p>by the Wall Street news.</p>
        <p>MARIE C. WALSH, Brooklyn</p>
        <p>Trees</p>
        <p>line up</p>
        <p>the highway.</p>
        <p>Raccoons lined up</p>
        <p>your neighbor's driveway.</p>
        <p>People scratching paper -</p>
        <p>using pencils pick numbers</p>
        <p>lined up in the newspaper store</p>
        <p>A raccoon in a tree wonders why!</p>
        <p>IMO HUGHES, North White Plains</p>
        <p>We</p>
        <p>live in</p>
        <p>Westchester.</p>
        <p>Our everyday</p>
        <p>life is not simple.</p>
        <p>When we want groceries,</p>
        <p>we go to the A&amp;P.</p>
        <p>Everyday we go out to play and</p>
        <p>look around pretty Westchester.</p>
        <p>AMY ROSVALLY and MAGGIE McNAMARA, Grade 4 Miller Elementary School, Katonah</p>
        <p>A</p>
        <p>robin</p>
        <p>zooms into</p>
        <p>my glass window</p>
        <p>In pursuit of what?</p>
        <p>His fair amorata,</p>
        <p>delectable wriggly worms,</p>
        <p>fountains of water and/or youth</p>
        <p>or merely an image of himself?</p>
        <p>MARGARET WEINSTOCK, Mamaroneck</p>
        <p>I</p>
        <p>live here</p>
        <p>white, big house.</p>
        <p>We sleep in there.</p>
        <p>We have lots of food.</p>
        <p>I am an immigrant.</p>
        <p>I like my big house a lot.</p>
        <p>I have one hundred fifteen cents.</p>
        <p>My family lives in Westchester.</p>
        <p>KYOHEI OTSUKA, Grade 2 Concord Road School, Ardsley</p>
        <p>Sail</p>
        <p>Sundays</p>
        <p>Steady breeze.</p>
        <p>Broad reach beyond</p>
        <p>Workday thoughts that drift</p>
        <p>Like flotsam in the mind.</p>
        <p>Come about with full regard</p>
        <p>Of compass course and change the spar.</p>
        <p>Dare the wind to catch you unaware!</p>
        <p>CAROLYN LANE, Ossining</p>
        <p>'Please</p>
        <p>don't squeeze</p>
        <p>the Charmin,'</p>
        <p>wrote Chervokas.</p>
        <p>Now he's a poet</p>
        <p>and Town Supervisor</p>
        <p>of Ossining. His next move?</p>
        <p>Dreaming up the pyrameter</p>
        <p>to squeeze words into a charming form.</p>
        <p>SONDRA AUDIN ARMER, Ossining</p>
        <p>IN WRITING</p>
      </block>
